The official syllabus groups outcomes into three categories.


A student can:

explain statistical distributions and where they arise in biological data;
distinguish Bayesian from frequentist approaches;
describe the solution space of a system of linear equations (unique, none, infinitely many);
explain what a latent space is and why dimensional reduction is useful.




A student can:

solve systems of linear equations (by hand for small systems, in R for larger ones);
formulate a biological problem as a Markov chain and analyse its behaviour;
analyse large-scale data using latent-space methods (PCA / OLS);
apply chemometrics to a biological dataset.




A student can:

assess the validity of a mathematical model for a biological system — state its assumptions and recognise when they break.

A tiny concrete 2-state HMM
States \(\{H, L\}\) — H = “GC-rich (high)”, L = “normal (low)”. Symbols: the bases \(\{A, C, G, T\}\).
\[
\boldsymbol{\pi}=\begin{bmatrix} 0.5 \\ 0.5 \end{bmatrix}, \qquad
A=\begin{array}{cc}
& \begin{array}{cc} H & L \end{array}\\
\begin{array}{c} H\\ L \end{array} &
\left[\begin{array}{cc} 0.8 & 0.2 \\ 0.3 & 0.7 \end{array}\right]
\end{array}
\]
\[
B=\begin{array}{c}
\begin{array}{cccc} \ A\  & \ C\  & \ G\  & \ T\  \end{array}\\
\begin{array}{c} \end{array}
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
0.1 & 0.4 & 0.4 & 0.1 \\
0.3 & 0.2 & 0.2 & 0.3
\end{array}\right]
\end{array}
\begin{array}{c} H\\ L \end{array}
\]
Read \(B\): state \(H\) emits C or G with prob 0.4 each (GC-rich!); state \(L\) spreads probability more evenly.

This is the example we will compute with by hand, and again in R tomorrow, so introduce it carefully. Pi says we start in either state with equal chance. A says both states are sticky — H stays H with probability 0.8, L stays L with 0.7 — which encodes that islands and background come in runs. B is the new object: the high state loves C and G, the low state is roughly uniform. Sanity check every row sums to one.
